The following specification gives a null pointer exception. The problem is to do with converting composed function values to name types.
```
types
    natfun = nat -> nat;

functions
    f: nat -> nat
    f(a) == a + 1;
   
    g: nat -> nat
    g(a) == a + 2;
   
    fg: () -> natfun    -- NOTE: returns a natfun
    fg() == f comp g;
   
    test: nat -> nat
    test(a) == fg()(a);
```

The specification below works correctly for T1, but fails on T2 (Overture 2.1.2) with an error: "Internal 0002: Cannot change type qualifier gets(nat1) to [nat1]".

It's fine in command line VDMJ.
```
class A
instance variables
	S : nat := init("instance");
	static Z : nat := init("static");

operations
	static init: seq of char ==> nat
	init(s) ==
	(
		IO`printf("-------------- Initialized %s ---------------\n", [s]);
		return 0
	);

	op: nat ==> nat
	op(n) ==
	(
		IO`printf("Called op(%s)\n", [n]);
		return n + 1
	);

	gets: nat ==> set of nat
	gets(n) ==
	(
		IO`printf("Called gets(%s)\n", [n]);
		S := S + 1;
		return {S+n, S+n+1}
	);

	getn: () ==> nat
	getn() ==
	(
		IO`println("Called getn()");
		return 0
	);


traces
	T1:
		let i = getn() in
		let s in set gets(i) in
			op(s);

	T2:
		|| (gets(1), gets(2), gets(3)); op(999);

end A
```

For the spec below the type checker raises an error claiming that "op1 is not in scope.", which it should be. The spec type checks without any errors in VDMJ.

~~~
class S

operations

public op1: () ==> ()
op1() == skip;

end S

class D is subclass of S

operations

public op2:() ==> ()
op2() == skip;

sync
per op2 => #active(op1) = 0;

end D
~~~

